    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-12-08T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-12-08T08:00:00-05:00" n="529"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d529">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">683.84A/12–852: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 529<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Syria (<persName corresp="#p_MJS1"
                            type="from">Moose</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d529fn1">Repeated to Tel Aviv, Amman, Baghdad, Beirut,
                        Cairo, London, and Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Damascus</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-12-08T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >December 8, 1952—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>411. Tel Aviv <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 902, December 3. Limited
                    quantity arms for Syr need not lessen chances Syro–Israeli agrmt. Strong regime
                    in Damascus can more effectively carry out policy of conciliation. Only major
                    Syr agrmts on sensitive issues since Pal war have been concluded by strong
                    Govts: <gloss target="#t_Tapline1">Tapline</gloss> concession and Syro-Israel
                    armistice by Zaim, and <gloss target="#t_UNRWA1">UNRWA</gloss> agrmt by
                    Shishikli. That supply of arms enhances Western influence in Syr demonstrated by
                    French and more recently by UK (Embdes 314 November 20).<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d529fn2">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Against advantages to West of promotion stable and friendly regime in Arab
                    states, Israeli arguments against delivery UK jets would seem carry little
                    weight. Israel reliance should surely not be placed on keeping surrounding
                    states impotent and unsatisfied but rather on increasing coop among mutually
                    self-respecting states in context tripartite declaration and eventual area
                    defense arrangements.</p>
                <p>ReEmbtel 400 December 1<note n="3" xml:id="d529fn3">Not printed, but see <ref
                            target="#d528fn4">footnote 4, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_MAC1">MAC</gloss> chairman <persName corresp="#p_TCS1"
                        >Taxis</persName> confirms he forwarded to Israel reps several weeks ago Syr
                    message indicating <gloss target="#t_GOS1">GOS</gloss> willingness resume
                    discussions. If, as described Tel Aviv <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss>
                    665 October 23, Israel is interested “in making [peace] with neighbors and
                    becoming integrated in region,” difficult see why Israel so slow in responding
                    forthrightly to Syr initiative on zone discussion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moose</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
